[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex Â· **Phase:** Regulated Â· **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on episode complexity, number of integrated systems, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, and care-management-team escalation overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Robert is 67. Eleven days ago he had a stroke. Not a catastrophic one, the kind that shows up with one-sided weakness and slurred speech and gets worked up in the emergency department, gets a CT and an MRI and an echocardiogram and a carotid doppler, gets admitted to the stroke unit, and gets discharged five days later with most of his function intact and a small permanent deficit in his left hand and a list, written on a piece of paper folded into the discharge envelope his wife is holding when they walk out of the hospital, of seventeen things he is supposed to do.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The list, in approximately the order it appears on the paper: pick up his new prescriptions (apixaban for atrial fibrillation, atorvastatin titrated up from his old dose, a new blood pressure medication added to his existing regimen, the old medication that he is now supposed to stop), see his primary care physician within seven days for medication reconciliation, see neurology in two to four weeks to review the work-up and discuss long-term secondary prevention, get a follow-up echocardiogram in three months because they saw something on the inpatient one that needs to be re-imaged, get a sleep study because they suspect undiagnosed sleep apnea contributed, start outpatient physical therapy three times a week for at least six weeks for the residual hand weakness, start outpatient occupational therapy twice a week for fine motor recovery, see ophthalmology because they want to rule out a related visual field defect, see cardiology in six weeks because the atrial fibrillation diagnosis is new and needs to be managed by someone who is not the neurologist, follow up with the hospital's stroke clinic in thirty days, attend a stroke-survivor support group the social worker recommended, get a home safety evaluation that the discharge planner referred but did not schedule, file paperwork with his employer's short-term disability carrier, contact the Social Security office about whether he might qualify for SSDI given the residual deficit and his age, contact his insurance about a new prior authorization for one of the medications, talk to his daughter about whether she should come stay for a few weeks, and call the hospital billing office about the bill for the inpatient stay that has not arrived yet but is going to arrive and is going to be a problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Robert's wife, Linda, is 64, retired from a school administration job, a person who had a planner in 1987 and still has one in 2026, and is spectacularly competent at logistics. Linda has the discharge envelope, two pages of typed discharge instructions, three pages of medication reconciliation that disagree subtly with each other on doses, the prescription printouts, four printed-out brochures about stroke that say substantially the same thing in different fonts, a card for the stroke clinic with a phone number, a card for the social worker with a phone number, a card for the case manager with a phone number, a card for the cardiologist who came by on hospital day three with a phone number, a printed referral for outpatient PT that does not specify a clinic, a printed referral for outpatient OT that does not specify a clinic, a printed referral for the sleep study that lists three possible providers and does not say which one is in network, and a piece of paper with the patient portal credentials that Robert has not used since 2019. Linda is, in this moment, the care coordinator. The healthcare system has assumed she will be, and is paying her zero dollars per hour to do it. Linda will spend approximately the next two weeks on the phone, and will not get all of it done before something falls through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here is what falls through, statistically. The PCP appointment in seven days will get scheduled, but the PCP's office will not have the discharge summary, which the hospital sent to a fax number that has not worked since 2022. <!-- TODO: verify; fax-based clinical-records exchange remains common and is a documented source of care-transition failures, with surveys consistently showing that PCPs receive discharge summaries late or not at all in a substantial fraction of post-discharge transitions; specific figures vary by study --> The PCP will spend the first ten minutes of the visit reconstructing what happened in the hospital from Robert's recollection, which is incomplete because Robert was on dexmedetomidine for the first thirty hours of his stay. The neurology appointment will get scheduled at twenty-eight days because that is the next available, not at fourteen. The follow-up echocardiogram in three months will not get scheduled at all, because the discharging team assumed the cardiologist would order it and the cardiologist will assume the discharging team did. The sleep study referral will sit in a queue at the sleep lab for nineteen days before someone calls Robert, who will let the call go to voicemail because the caller ID was unfamiliar. The PT referral will be filled by Linda calling three clinics until one has appointments within a week; the OT referral will not be filled at all because Linda will run out of energy and reasonably assume PT and OT are kind of the same thing. The ophthalmology referral will not get scheduled because Robert will quietly conclude that his vision is fine. The stroke-clinic follow-up at thirty days will get rescheduled twice and will eventually happen at fifty-three days. The home safety evaluation will not happen. The new apixaban prescription will be denied at the pharmacy on day three because the prior authorization the hospital pharmacy was supposed to initiate did not get initiated, and Linda will spend ninety minutes on the phone with the insurance company on day four to fix it, during which Robert will not take his stroke-prevention anticoagulation. <!-- TODO: verify; care-transition failures involving missed referrals, missed follow-ups, prescription gaps from prior-authorization issues, and inadequate medication reconciliation are well-documented in the post-discharge literature, including the landmark Project RED studies, the Society of Hospital Medicine's BOOST program, and the Re-Engineered Discharge program work; specific failure rates vary by study --> Forty-seven days after discharge, Robert will have done about sixty percent of what was on the list. Eight months after discharge, Robert will have a second stroke, which a follow-up paper in a quality-improvement journal might attribute to the gaps in the post-discharge plan but more likely will not, because the journal does not have the data to do that attribution and the patient does not appear in any single denominator that anyone is monitoring. <!-- TODO: verify; secondary stroke risk after first stroke is meaningfully elevated, with cumulative risk reduced substantially by adherence to evidence-based secondary prevention including anticoagulation for atrial-fibrillation-associated stroke, statin therapy, blood pressure control, and rehabilitation; specific risk reduction figures vary by study and population -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the story of post-discharge care transitions in the United States, and it is the story of essentially every multi-specialist condition. It is the story of a newly-diagnosed cancer patient navigating between the surgeon, the medical oncologist, the radiation oncologist, the genetic counselor, the social worker, the financial counselor, the pharmacy, and the patient assistance program. It is the story of an end-stage kidney disease patient navigating between the nephrologist, the dialysis access surgeon, the transplant coordinator, the dietitian, the cardiology clearance, the dental clearance, the social work evaluation, the financial aid office, and the dialysis unit. It is the story of a child with autism navigating between the developmental pediatrician, the speech therapist, the occupational therapist, the behavioral therapist, the school district's IEP team, the insurance care manager, and the parent advocacy organization. It is the story of a high-risk pregnancy navigating between the obstetrician, the maternal-fetal medicine specialist, the genetic counselor, the perinatologist, the anesthesiologist, the nutritionist, the lactation consultant, the social worker, the doula, and the pediatrician for the upcoming delivery. It is the story, in short, of every patient whose care does not fit inside a single twenty-minute office visit and instead lives in the weeks and months between visits, in the spaces between providers, in the gaps between systems that do not exchange information, in the queues that do not move, in the prior authorizations that do not arrive, in the referrals that get faxed to numbers that do not work, in the scheduling phone trees that route to voicemail, and in the patient or family member or, if they are very lucky, the nurse care manager who is trying to hold the whole thing together with a planner and a phone and a level of patience that should be illegal to require of a sick person.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The economics make the problem worse, not better. Care-coordination breakdowns are one of the largest sources of avoidable cost, avoidable suffering, and avoidable harm in the entire healthcare system. <!-- TODO: verify; the cost and quality consequences of poor care coordination are documented in IOM and National Academy of Medicine reports, AHRQ patient-safety literature, and CMS quality measurement programs that explicitly target care-transition outcomes; specific figures vary by methodology and the conditions included --> A patient who misses a post-discharge follow-up because the records did not arrive is statistically more likely to be readmitted. A patient whose secondary-prevention medication has a prior-authorization gap is statistically more likely to have a recurrent event. A patient whose specialist referral never gets scheduled is statistically more likely to have a worse outcome from the underlying condition. Each of these events is, individually, one of the most expensive things that happens in healthcare. The cost of effective care coordination, even at fairly aggressive levels, is meaningfully smaller than the cost of any one of these downstream events, and the math has been clear to actuaries and to value-based-care leaders for at least a decade. The reason most members of the population do not get effective care coordination is not that the math doesn't work; it's that the labor model for nurse care coordination does not scale to the population that would benefit. Nurse care coordinators exist. They are heroic. They are expensive, finite, and reserved for the highest-risk members in capitated populations. Robert, with one stroke and one comorbidity, is not high-risk enough to qualify. Robert and his wife, doing the care coordination themselves, are the population the system implicitly assumes will be the default care coordinator, and that assumption is, to put it mildly, not always correct.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generation of digital tools tried to address this with patient portals, scheduling apps, and (in the better products) longitudinal records views. The clinical evidence for these tools, at the level of actually closing care-coordination gaps, was thin. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for patient-portal effects on care-coordination outcomes shows mixed results with the strongest effects in engaged patients with already-good health literacy and the weakest effects in the populations with the highest care-coordination needs --> The fundamental problem these products had was that they presented information without doing the work of coordination. A patient portal that lets you see all your upcoming appointments is not the same thing as a system that schedules them, follows up when they are missed, makes sure the records arrive at each visit, surfaces the next thing you need to do, and escalates to a human when something has fallen through. The portal is a record viewer. The patient still does the coordination. For patients with the resources to coordinate (a competent family member, the time, the literacy, the comfort with phone calls, the language match), the portal helps. For patients without those resources, the portal is, at best, neutral, and at worst, an extra system to ignore.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2023, is that conversational AI got good enough, and tool-using LLM patterns got reliable enough, to make care-coordination assistance feel like a relationship with a competent navigator rather than a checklist. A patient who would not log into the portal, would not call the case manager's voicemail, would not fill out the referral-tracking form, will sometimes respond to a text message that says "Hi Robert, just checking in. The hospital sent a referral over for outpatient PT. I see you haven't scheduled yet. Want me to look up clinics near you that are in your network, or would you rather call yourself?" That message comes from a system that has read the discharge summary, knows what referrals are open, knows what is scheduled and what is not, knows the patient's insurance network, knows the patient's home address, and knows what to say next based on the institution's care-coordination protocol. The system is not a person. The patient mostly knows that. The patient also, in the right product design, talks to it anyway, because the alternative was figuring out the next step alone, and because the message is genuinely useful, and because the system holds the whole care plan in working memory in a way the patient and their family cannot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that system. The care coordination assistant is the conversational AI use case where multi-system integration is the dominant architectural challenge, where episode-level state management spans weeks or months, and where the cost of a missed handoff between systems can be measured in real harm to real patients. It inherits patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes (FAQ, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits, triage, chronic disease coaching, mental health support) and adds several entirely new ones: closed-loop referral tracking across organizational boundaries, care-transition state machines, multi-provider context reconciliation, cross-system records exchange monitoring, episode-of-care timelines, and the delicate business of being useful to a patient whose care plan is being executed by a dozen different organizations that do not talk to each other very well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that helps patients (and their family caregivers) navigate complex care journeys involving multiple providers, multiple visits, multiple referrals, multiple care-transitions, multiple records exchanges, and multiple administrative tasks; it knows what is scheduled and what is not, what is completed and what is open, what records have arrived and what have not; it proactively surfaces the next thing the patient needs to do; it answers patient questions about their care plan and current status; it integrates with scheduling, referral, prior authorization, and records-exchange systems to actually do the coordination work, not just describe it; and it escalates to a human care coordinator when the situation calls for one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not the patient's primary care team. The bot extends what a nurse care coordinator can do; it does not replace the clinical judgment that the care team brings. The recommendations the bot surfaces are recommendations that have been pre-authorized in the patient's care plan or in the institution's care-coordination protocol, not new clinical recommendations the bot is making.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers longitudinal coaching for chronic conditions. The care coordination assistant is episode-focused and transition-focused: a post-discharge episode, a new-diagnosis workup, a multi-specialist evaluation, a transitions-of-care window. The two recipes can coexist for the same patient (and often should), but the architectural focus is different. Coaching is about the months and years of managing an established chronic condition; coordination is about the weeks and months of navigating an episode of care that involves many actors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. The care coordination assistant assumes the patient's clinical picture is already known and is being managed by their care team; when the patient surfaces an acute symptom, the bot routes to triage workflows or to direct emergency contacts. The coordination assistant does not try to do triage from scratch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a benefits navigator. Recipe 11.5 covers insurance-benefits questions. The coordination assistant deals with benefits-adjacent issues that arise during care coordination (a denied prior authorization, a referral that needs in-network steering, a service that requires pre-certification) but escalates to the benefits navigator or to the institution's benefits team for substantive coverage questions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a scheduling bot, although it uses one. Recipe 11.2 covers scheduling. The coordination assistant invokes scheduling capabilities as part of coordination work, but its scope is broader than booking appointments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the patient or family doing some of the coordination work. The patient is still the patient. The family caregiver is still the family caregiver. The bot reduces the load and surfaces the things that are at risk of falling through; it does not, and should not, take over the patient's agency in their own care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-system product. Care coordination, by definition, spans multiple systems: the EHR, the scheduling system, the referral management system, the prior authorization system, the pharmacy system, the lab system, the imaging system, the rehabilitation system, the home health system, the social services system, the patient's various external providers' systems, the payer's eligibility system, the records-exchange network or HIE, and (for patients who have one) the care-management system. The architecture is, fundamentally, an integration architecture. Most of the engineering investment is in the integrations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Patient-facing care-coordination software handles PHI from multiple sources, makes patient-facing recommendations about care steps, sometimes touches medication and prior-authorization workflows, and may sit on or near the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line depending on what specifically the system does. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's 2022 final guidance on Clinical Decision Support software addresses some patient-facing software, but the regulatory positioning of care-coordination software depends on the specific recommendations the software produces; the regulatory landscape continues to evolve --> The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters, not sprints. The integration work is multi-quarter. The protocol-design work is multi-quarter. The escalation-pathway work is multi-quarter. The outcome-demonstration work is multi-year. Institutions building this expecting a fast time-to-value are usually disappointed. Institutions building this with realistic timelines and the patience to build the integration substrate carefully are sometimes able to demonstrate genuinely meaningful improvements in care-transition outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the assistant's value is concentrated in three places, and not in the one most engineers think first. First: the closed-loop discipline (knowing what is open, what is scheduled, what is completed, what is at risk, and what has fallen through, across many systems, in real time, for many patients at once). Second: the proactive surfacing (initiating the conversation when something needs attention, rather than waiting for the patient to know to ask). Third: the warm handoff to a human care coordinator when the situation calls for one (not the bot solving every problem, the bot routing the right problems to the right human at the right time). The conversational interface is the visible part; the integration substrate and the closed-loop tracking are most of the engineering.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
