Purpose: Append Technology section

[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Multi-System Integration, Episode-of-Care State, and Closed-Loop Coordination Discipline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Care Coordination Has Resisted Software Solutions For Twenty Years
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care coordination, as a clinical workflow, has been a phone-and-fax-and-clipboard problem for as long as the modern healthcare system has existed. The reason is structural and is essentially the reason American healthcare is fragmented in the first place. The patient's care is delivered by many independent organizations, with their own systems, their own data conventions, their own scheduling processes, their own authorization processes, their own clinical staff, their own billing departments, and their own institutional priorities. The patient sits at the center, often unaware that they are sitting at the center, while these organizations exchange (or fail to exchange) records, referrals, results, authorizations, and instructions on the patient's behalf. When everything works, the patient experiences a coherent journey. When something does not work, the patient is the one who notices, often too late, and the system has no built-in mechanism to detect or repair the gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of care-coordination software, roughly 1995 to 2010, tried to address this with care management modules inside electronic health records and standalone care-coordination products that lived in the gaps between systems. These products were primarily aimed at nurse care managers, who used them to keep track of their assigned panels. They worked within a single organization and largely did not solve the cross-organization problem. They were used by a small number of professional users on behalf of a small number of high-risk patients, and the rest of the population was uncoordinated by default. <!-- TODO: verify; care-management software adoption in the 2000s and 2010s focused largely on payer and accountable-care-organization care management, with limited reach into provider organizations and limited cross-organizational integration; specific adoption figures vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2010 to 2020, tried to address this by giving the patient a portal. The patient could log in, see their appointments, see their messages, see their results, and (in some products) self-schedule. The clinical evidence for portals at the level of closing care-coordination gaps was thin. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on patient-portal effects on care-coordination outcomes shows mixed results, with the strongest effects in already-engaged patients and limited effects in the populations with the highest care-coordination needs --> The portal was a record viewer, not a coordinator. The patient still did the coordination, but now had a record to look at while doing it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The third generation, roughly 2018 to 2024, tried to address this with workflow tools layered on top of the EHR: referral-management modules, transitions-of-care modules, post-discharge follow-up modules. These improved internal coordination within an organization but still struggled with cross-organizational coordination. The HL7 FHIR specifications, the 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions, and the TEFCA framework for nationwide health information exchange were beginning to provide the technical and regulatory substrate for cross-organizational data exchange, with progress that was real but uneven across regions and across organization types. <!-- TODO: verify; FHIR adoption, Cures Act information-blocking enforcement, and TEFCA implementation continue to evolve, with substantial regional variation in cross-organizational data exchange capability; specific figures vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape, around 2023, is that conversational AI got good enough to make care-coordination assistance feel like talking to a competent navigator rather than navigating a portal. A patient who would not log into a portal will, sometimes, respond to a text message. A patient who would not call a case manager's voicemail will, sometimes, ask a chat assistant a question. A patient who would not fill out a referral-tracking form will, sometimes, tell a bot "I haven't scheduled the PT yet, where do I go?" The bot, in the right architecture, has the patient's care plan in working memory, knows what is scheduled and what is not, knows what records have arrived and what have not, knows the patient's insurance network, knows the patient's home address, and knows the next thing to do. The bot is not a nurse care coordinator. The bot is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the nurse-care-coordinator workflow operate at population scale by handling the routine touches and surfacing the cases that need human judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "record viewer" to "closed-loop coordinator with conversational interface." The assistant's value is concentrated in three places: the closed-loop tracking discipline (every referral, every appointment, every records exchange, every prior authorization has a state and a follow-up; nothing falls through silently), the proactive surfacing (the bot initiates engagement when something needs attention, not just when the patient logs in), and the multi-system integration (the bot has visibility across the systems involved in the patient's care, not just the one institution that owns the bot).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Care Coordination Assistant Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A care coordination assistant is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that describes its scope, the patient's authenticated context, the patient's active care-coordination episodes, the active referrals and their states, the scheduled and unscheduled appointments, the open records-exchange items, the open prior-authorization items, and the institution's care-coordination protocols for the relevant episode types. The conversation surface is a stream of episodes, sometimes patient-initiated, often bot-initiated based on care-plan milestones, on records-exchange events (a referral note arrived, a result came back), or on inactivity timers (a referral has not been scheduled in fourteen days).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode initiation and care-plan loading.** A care-coordination episode is initiated by a discrete event: a hospital discharge, a new diagnosis with a multi-specialist workup, a treatment-plan kickoff (chemotherapy, dialysis access, transplant evaluation), a transitions-of-care event (skilled nursing facility to home, primary to specialist), or a payer-side enrollment in a care-coordination program. The episode is instantiated from a protocol template (the institution's standard post-stroke discharge protocol, the institution's standard new-cancer-diagnosis workup protocol, etc.) with patient-specific values. The episode has an expected timeline, a set of required milestones, and a set of escalation criteria. The patient receives an introductory message explaining the episode and what the bot will do.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop tracking of every coordination element.** Each referral, each appointment, each records exchange, each prior authorization, each task on the discharge or care plan has a state, a target date, and a follow-up rule. The bot maintains visibility into the state of each element across the multiple systems that own them. When an element is not progressing per the protocol, the bot surfaces it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Proactive engagement with the patient at the right moments.** A few examples. A referral was created but not scheduled within seven days: the bot reaches out to ask if the patient needs help finding a clinic. A scheduled appointment is in two days and the receiving provider does not have the records: the bot reaches out to confirm that the patient knows about the appointment and reminds them what to bring. An imaging result has arrived but not been reviewed yet: the bot does not engage the patient yet (the result needs to be reviewed by the ordering provider first). A prior authorization is approved: the bot lets the patient know they can fill the prescription. A prior authorization is denied: the bot routes to the benefits navigator or to a human care coordinator. A scheduled visit is in two days and the patient has open pre-visit forms: the bot reminds the patient. A patient missed a scheduled visit: the bot reaches out to ask if everything is okay and offers to help reschedule. The proactive engagement is calibrated to be useful, not surveillance-flavored, and the institutional engagement-policy rules from the chronic-disease coach apply.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated questions about the care plan.** Patients ask things. "When is my MRI?" "Did the doctor see my labs yet?" "What was I supposed to bring to the appointment?" "Did the prior auth come through?" "Do I really need the OT or is the PT enough?" "When does my next refill go in?" "I haven't heard back from the cardiology office, what should I do?" The bot answers within scope using grounded retrieval over the patient's care plan, the institution's coordination protocol, the relevant external system data, and the conversation history.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Scheduling and rescheduling assistance.** The bot can search for available appointments, hold a slot, confirm with the patient, and finalize a booking through the institution's scheduling integration. The bot can reschedule when the patient cannot make a visit. The bot does not unilaterally schedule visits without patient confirmation; the patient retains agency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Records-exchange tracking and surfacing.** The bot watches for records moving between the institution's systems and external providers (or the records-exchange network if one is in use). When records arrive late, the bot surfaces the gap to the appropriate workflow. When the patient is going to a provider who does not have the records, the bot can offer to share the patient's portal credentials, summarize the relevant care, or trigger an alert to the care-coordination team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prior-authorization status tracking.** The bot tracks the state of prior authorizations relevant to the patient's care plan. When an authorization is approved, denied, or pending appeal, the bot communicates appropriately. The bot does not make medical-necessity arguments to the payer; that is recipe 2.4 (prior auth letter generation). The bot tracks state and surfaces it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-transition support.** When the patient is transitioning from one care setting to another (hospital to home, hospital to skilled nursing facility, primary to specialist, treatment to maintenance), the bot supports the transition with the institution's transitions-of-care protocol: the post-discharge call timing, the medication-reconciliation prompt, the follow-up-appointment confirmation, the symptom-monitoring per the discharge plan, and the escalation criteria.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Education and content delivery in coordination context.** The bot delivers patient-education content (drawn from the institution's curated library) at moments when it is contextually relevant to the coordination episode: pre-visit content before scheduled visits, post-visit content after, condition-specific content during a new-diagnosis workup, transition-specific content during a care transition. The content is grounded in the institution's clinical and patient-experience leadership signoff.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-team escalation.** When the situation calls for a human (a complex prior-authorization appeal, a clinical question outside the bot's scope, a sensitive disclosure, a patient request for a human, an apparent decompensation, a coordination problem the bot cannot resolve), the bot escalates to the appropriate human resource per the institution's policy. The escalation includes the conversation context, the relevant coordination state, and the reason for escalation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop completion and episode wrap-up.** When the coordination episode is complete (all milestones met, the patient stable on the new regimen, the new-diagnosis workup completed and the patient transitioned to standard ongoing management), the bot wraps up the episode with a summary to the patient and to the care team, and steps back. Some patients move directly into chronic-disease coaching (recipe 11.7) for ongoing management. Some return to standard care.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some discharge instructions, and have it help the patient. This breaks in several specific ways, each with operational and clinical consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of what is actually happening in the systems.** A care coordination assistant without integrations is a chatbot with discharge instructions. The patient asks "did my referral get scheduled?" and the bot does not know. The architecture is, fundamentally, an integration architecture; the LLM is the conversational interface to the integrations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of episode state.** A care-coordination episode is a state machine: start state (just discharged, or just diagnosed, or just enrolled), intermediate states (PT scheduled but not yet attended; cardiology scheduled in three weeks; sleep study referred but not scheduled), and end states (all milestones met, patient stable, episode closed). Without explicit state, the bot has no way to know what is on track, what is at risk, and what has fallen through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to engage proactively.** The assistant's value depends substantially on proactive engagement: surfacing referrals that have not been scheduled, reminding about visits that need pre-visit prep, escalating prior authorizations that are stuck, alerting the care team when something has fallen through. A reactive bot that only responds when the patient initiates is not a coordinator; it is a chatbot.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of what each system means.** The patient's referral lives in the referral management module. The appointment lives in the scheduling system. The records exchange lives in the HIE or in the institution's interoperability layer. The prior authorization lives in the payer's portal and in the institution's revenue-cycle system. The lab result lives in the lab system and the clinical-record system. Each has its own data model, its own state semantics, its own latency, and its own failure modes. The bot's tools have to encode this knowledge; the LLM does not learn it on its own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications across multiple data sources.** The bot is reading PHI from multiple systems (sometimes including external providers' systems) and writing back to several. The audit, retention, access-control, downstream-clinical-workflow integration, and cross-organization data-sharing posture has to handle each.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-organization records exchange.** When a patient is going to an external provider, did the records arrive? When the patient comes back from an external provider, did the consult note arrive? The bot's records-exchange-tracking layer answers these questions; the LLM does not have visibility into HIE traffic or fax queues without explicit integrations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to escalate.** The bot knows what it is supposed to do per the protocol. It does not know how to handle a sudden insurance-coverage termination mid-treatment, a patient disclosure that a family member is dying and they cannot attend visits, an unexpected prior-authorization denial that requires medical-necessity letter generation, a patient who is becoming uncertain about the entire treatment plan. Each of these is a moment for human judgment; the bot's escalation logic is encoded explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the patient agency boundary.** The bot can schedule appointments only if the patient confirms. The bot can request records only with appropriate authorization. The bot can communicate with external providers only per the patient's release-of-information posture. The bot can surface coordination state only consistent with the institution's data-governance policy and the patient's consent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems.** Care-coordination protocols sometimes encode timing rules (the post-discharge follow-up should be within seven days; the secondary-prevention medication should start within thirty days), threshold rules (more than three missed appointments triggers care-management escalation), and aggregation rules (the patient has completed sixty percent of milestones, the patient is on track). The LLM does this poorly. The deterministic protocol-rule tools encapsulate the computation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has integration-failure-mode handling problems.** External systems go down. APIs rate-limit. Records exchange has latency. The bot needs to handle these gracefully, surface degradation rather than misinform the patient, and route to a human when the integration story is not working. The graceful-degradation logic is part of the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of patient context outside the coordination episode.** The patient may have a chronic disease coach, a mental-health support tool, a benefits navigator, a triage bot. The coordination assistant operates in concert with these, with appropriate handoff at the boundaries. A patient surfacing acute symptoms in a coordination conversation routes to triage; a patient surfacing emotional-support needs routes to the appropriate pathway; a patient surfacing benefits questions routes to the benefits navigator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has long-running-state-management problems.** Coordination episodes can run for weeks or months. The conversation history, the protocol state, the integration state, the patient's context are all state that needs to be maintained, periodically summarized, and made available to the next conversation. The longitudinal-store discipline from the chronic-disease coach applies, with episode-specific extensions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Coordination Assistant Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.8 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal context loading, citation grounding, behavior-change-stage tracking (where applicable), and crisis routing. The coordination assistant adds nine structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-system integration as architectural primitive.** The bot reads from and writes to many systems. The integration substrate (referral management, scheduling, records exchange, prior authorization, pharmacy, lab, imaging, home health, social services, payer eligibility, the institution's care-management system, and any relevant external systems) is the dominant engineering investment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-of-care state machine as architectural primitive.** Each coordination episode is a state machine instantiated from a protocol template, with patient-specific values, a timeline, milestones, and escalation criteria. The state is updated as events arrive from integrated systems. The bot operates within the state machine.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop tracking discipline.** Every coordination element (referral, appointment, records exchange, prior authorization, task) has a state, a target date, a follow-up rule, and a closed-loop completion event. The bot tracks each, surfaces what is at risk, and escalates what has fallen through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organization records-exchange monitoring.** When the patient's care involves external providers, records-exchange events (sent, received, missing) are first-class events the bot watches. Where the institution participates in HIE or TEFCA, the integration is with the network; where the institution exchanges via direct messaging, fax, or other modalities, the integration handles that.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-transition state management.** Care transitions (hospital to home, primary to specialist, treatment to maintenance, in to out of care management) have specific state machines with specific escalation criteria and time-bound milestones. The bot operates the relevant transition protocol per the patient's situation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode-level summarization and reporting.** The bot generates structured summaries at episode milestones and at episode close, for the care team, the patient, and (where applicable) external providers. The summaries are designed for the relevant audience.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management-team integration as first-class capability.** The bot is deployed alongside the institution's care-management workforce. Real-time alerts, weekly digests, individual conversation review, and feedback loops for protocol revision are part of production scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-system idempotency discipline.** Because the bot interacts with multiple systems, each potentially with their own retry semantics, the engagement and integration events are idempotent. Duplicate appointment bookings, duplicate referral creations, duplicate records requests are operational hazards.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-agency boundary enforcement.** The bot acts on the patient's behalf only with explicit authorization for each category of action. Scheduling needs patient confirmation. Records requests need release-of-information authorization. Cross-organization data sharing needs the appropriate consent. The architecture encodes these consent boundaries explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Coordination Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes care coordination specifically harder than the previous patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration is the engineering investment, not the LLM.** Most teams that come to this from a generalist conversational-AI background underestimate the integration work. The LLM is the visible part. The boring, multi-quarter, multi-team, contract-and-spec-and-ETL work of integrating with each system involved in the patient's care is most of the engineering. Institutions that try to skip the integration work and build a coordination assistant on top of a single-system view ship a chatbot, not a coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organization integration is harder than internal integration.** Internal integration with the institution's own systems is hard. Cross-organization integration with external providers' systems is harder. The records-exchange substrate is uneven. The data-sharing agreements are bilateral and bespoke. The patient-consent posture varies. The TEFCA and HIE substrate is improving but not uniformly available. <!-- TODO: verify; cross-organizational data-exchange capability in the U.S. continues to be uneven, with TEFCA implementation, HIE coverage, and direct-messaging adoption varying substantially by region and organization --> The architecture has to handle the heterogeneous integration landscape gracefully, with explicit handling of cases where the integration is not available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop tracking is an operational, not a technical, problem.** The technical part of closed-loop tracking (representing state, watching for events, surfacing what has fallen through) is straightforward. The operational part (ensuring that each system actually emits the events the loop depends on, that the events are reliable, that latency is acceptable, that errors are handled, that backfill works) is hard. Most institutions discover, partway through deployment, that the systems they thought emitted events do not actually emit them, or emit them inconsistently, or emit them with too much latency to be useful. The integration-quality investment is often larger than the engineering team initially expected.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient agency must be preserved with care.** A bot that acts on the patient's behalf without explicit authorization is a bot that erodes trust and creates regulatory exposure. The architecture encodes per-action consent: schedule with patient confirmation, request records with release-of-information authorization, communicate with external providers per the patient's posture. The friction this introduces is intentional.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Family and caregiver involvement is the rule, not the exception.** Many high-coordination-need patients are not the primary user of the coordination assistant; their family caregiver is. The architecture supports authorized-caregiver access with appropriate consent (HIPAA personal-representative provisions, state-specific caregiver-access laws, patient-designated proxy access), differentiates patient-self-engagement from caregiver engagement, and handles the cases where the patient and caregiver have different preferences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural and linguistic considerations are not optional.** The populations with the highest care-coordination needs are often the populations with the most limited access to coordination resources. A coordination assistant that operates only in English, only references one cultural framework around family decision-making, only handles one health-literacy level, is excluding the populations with the highest unmet need.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Health-literacy adaptation is critical.** Care-coordination conversations involve medical terminology, scheduling logistics, insurance terminology, and procedural details. A coordination assistant that delivers content at the wrong reading level is unusable for the patients who most need it. Reading-level adaptation, plain-language rendering, and visual-presentation alternatives (where the channel supports them) are part of the architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Social-determinants context is part of the coordination reality.** A patient who cannot afford the copay for their PT will not go. A patient who has no transportation cannot attend their cardiology follow-up across town. A patient who works two jobs cannot attend midday lab visits. A patient with unstable housing cannot reliably receive mailed materials or scheduled phone calls. The coordination assistant's recommendations are clinical and logistical, but their feasibility is socially determined; the institution's deployment includes social-determinants overlays where possible, with care-navigation handoff for the cases that require it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Episode types vary considerably and have different protocols.** A post-stroke discharge is a different protocol from a new-cancer-diagnosis workup, which is a different protocol from a high-risk pregnancy, which is a different protocol from a transplant evaluation. The institution's protocol library is multi-quarter clinical work with named ownership at the appropriate clinical-specialty leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management-team capacity is a binding constraint.** The bot escalates to humans. The humans have finite capacity. Institutional engagement-policy and escalation-policy decisions calibrate the bot's escalation rate to the available human capacity. Deploying a bot whose escalation rate exceeds the care-management workforce's capacity produces an alert backlog and erodes care-team trust.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is medium-term work.** Care-transition outcomes (30-day readmission rates, post-discharge ED-visit rates, time-to-follow-up, completion of secondary-prevention milestones) are observable in months to a year, faster than chronic-disease outcomes. Cross-organization outcomes (closed-loop referral completion, care-plan-element completion rate, patient-reported coordination quality) are observable similarly. The outcome correlation is part of the launch commitment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningfully concentrated in the missed-handoff scenarios.** A bot that fails to surface a referral that has not been scheduled, where the patient subsequently has a worse outcome, has foreseeable liability exposure. The institutional malpractice carrier is part of the policy review; the institutional liability counsel reviews the bot's design, scope discipline, escalation pathway, and audit posture; and the institution's risk management team is involved in the launch readiness review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR specifications now cover the relevant care-coordination resources.** The HL7 FHIR specification includes resources for ServiceRequest (referrals), Appointment, CarePlan, Goal, Task, CareTeam, EpisodeOfCare, and Communication. <!-- TODO: verify; the FHIR specification's care-coordination resources continue to evolve, with US Core profiles defining specific U.S. implementation expectations; specific resource-and-profile coverage varies by implementation --> Institutional deployments increasingly use FHIR-native data models for the bot's coordination state, integrating with the institution's FHIR API surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **TEFCA and the QHIN framework are providing the substrate for nationwide records exchange.** The Trusted Exchange Framework and Common Agreement, with Qualified Health Information Networks operationally connected since 2024, provides a path for patient-mediated and treatment-purpose records exchange across organizational boundaries. <!-- TODO: verify; TEFCA implementation has continued since the December 2023 designation of initial QHINs and the ongoing onboarding of additional networks; the operational coverage and use-case scope continues to expand --> Institutional deployments increasingly integrate with QHIN connectivity for cross-organization records exchange.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The 21st Century Cures Act information-blocking provisions are operationally enforced.** Healthcare organizations and certified health IT vendors must not engage in information-blocking practices, with HHS-OIG civil monetary penalties and ONC disincentive policies as enforcement mechanisms. <!-- TODO: verify; ONC information-blocking enforcement has continued to evolve since the implementation of the Cures Act final rules, with both penalties and the public scrutiny of complaint patterns shaping organizational behavior --> The regulatory environment is increasingly favorable for cross-organization data exchange that supports patient-mediated care coordination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-mediated data access is increasingly capable.** Patient-facing FHIR APIs (the SMART Health IT framework, Apple Health Records, Google Health Connect, the patient-access apps required by various state laws) increasingly let patients aggregate their own records across organizations. <!-- TODO: verify; patient-mediated data-aggregation tools have matured since the implementation of the Cures Act patient-access requirements and continue to evolve --> Coordination assistants can increasingly leverage patient-aggregated views for cross-organizational visibility.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle multi-system coordination orchestration well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from previous chapter 11 recipes maps to coordination. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve referral state, retrieve appointment state, retrieve records-exchange state, retrieve prior-authorization state, schedule appointments (with patient confirmation), request records, surface escalation flags, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop referral programs are operationally standard at major systems.** Most major health systems and large medical groups operate some form of closed-loop referral program, often within their internal network and increasingly across networks where TEFCA or HIE connectivity supports it. <!-- TODO: verify; closed-loop referral program adoption has matured at major U.S. health systems with significant variation in cross-organizational coverage; specific figures vary --> The coordination assistant operates within the institution's closed-loop referral substrate and extends it to the patient surface.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management software continues to evolve from desktop to integrated platforms.** Modern care-management platforms increasingly integrate with the EHR, the scheduling system, the referral management module, the prior-authorization system, the patient-engagement surface, and (for value-based-care contexts) the population-health analytics layer. <!-- TODO: verify; care-management platform consolidation and integration have continued, with major EHR vendors offering integrated care-management modules and standalone vendors operating at scale --> The coordination assistant integrates with the institution's care-management platform rather than reinventing one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-human coordination is the dominant production pattern.** Most major deployments run a hybrid model: AI assistant for routine coordination touches, with human care-coordinator availability for high-complexity members, escalation cases, and patient-requested human contact. The economics work because the AI handles the routine elements while the human focuses where their judgment is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome demonstration is mixed but trending positive.** Studies of digital and digital-plus-human care-coordination programs have shown improvements in time-to-follow-up, completion-of-care-plan-elements, 30-day readmission rates, patient-reported coordination quality, and (in some programs) downstream cost reduction, with the strongest evidence for hybrid programs in specific patient populations. <!-- TODO: verify; the evidence base for digital care-coordination programs includes studies of post-discharge follow-up programs, transitions-of-care programs, and care-management-extension programs; specific outcome figures vary by study and population --> The evidence is suggestive that the architectural pattern in this recipe, deployed carefully, can produce meaningful improvements in care-transition outcomes for engaged populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity considerations are a major area of attention.** As with chronic-disease coaching, the risk that a coordination assistant reaches the patients who need it least and misses the patients who need it most is real. Per-cohort monitoring is essential, and the institutional commitment to equity is reviewed by the compliance and patient-experience teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several care-management and care-coordination vendors offer products at major-payer scale, with EHR integration, records-exchange integration, payer-system integration, and (in some cases) AI-assistant components. Most major institutions run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with vendors for licensed care-management workflow software, and integrate with the institution's care-management workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
